We have recommended to the Management to:
Direct the Department Heads concerned to immediately prepare a consolidated report on all management actions taken relative to the audit observations and recommendations included in the Annual Audit Report for CY 2019 using the prescribed AAPSI Form;
Strictly adhere to the prescribed period for submission of the AAPSI as provided under the GAA.

Recommendation

We recommended Management to:

Direct the Municipal Engineer to request the contractor to remove and replace the defects as soon as possible and impose applicable sanctions and penalties if warranted;  



Submit compliance report on the recommendations stated in the Technical Inspection Report if already rectified; 



Intensify the monitoring of all on-going projects to minimize defects and avoid deficiencies; and



Submit the Statement of Time Elapsed and Work Accomplished (STEWA) of the projects enumerated above.

Recommendations

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive should direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Dig up records available in the Accounting Office and conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the receivable accounts;



Determine if the accounts could already be classified as dormant accounts in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005;



We also recommended that the LCE should exhaust all possible remedies by the management to collect the receivables and to demand liquidation of cash advances and fund transfers. If it is still impractical to do so due to lack or absence of records, death or difficulty in locating the debtors, file the request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005.

Recommendations

We recommend that Management should:

Decide whether or not to permanently takeover the operation of the Laguindingan Water District;




Demand from the then governing board of the Laguindingan Water District inventory of their assets and liabilities, their financial records which includes creditors and consumers. Should the LGU decide to permanently takeover the LWD, the loan agreement between LWD and LWUA must also be turned over;

Require the then governing board of the LWD to submit proof of compliance with Section 44 of PD 198;



Coordinate with LWUA regarding the unilateral assumption of the Laguindingan Water District; and



Reflect proper accounting in the books of LGU should the LGU decide to permanently take over the LWD. The water district should be recognized as an economic enterprise of the LGU pursuant to Section 105 of the NGAS Manual and separate financial statements must also be prepared.

Recommendations

The Management should maximize the utilization of the 20% development fund allocated for the implementation of various projects, programs and activities that are envisioned to help in the attainment of social, economic and environmental development;




The Local Development Council should ensure the optimal utilization of the 20% Development Fund through proper planning of projects including timing of execution and strict monitoring of project implementation to ensure accomplishment of the PPAs.

